Ziziphus mauritiana

   [17633.jpg]
   Authority Lam.
   Family
   Synonyms Ziziphus jujuba Lam. (1879)., Rhamnus jujuba L. (1753).
   Common names ber, cottony , Indian jujube, desert apple, Chinese apple,
   jujubier, anafega da India, widara, bidara, manzanitas, phutsaa,
   putrea, than, tao nhuc, sidr, beri, gob, abateri, wag'n bietjie,
   mkunazi, gava, ghob, gheb, jumuba, kurkura (Galinya, Harar), gusura
   (Afargna)
   Editor
   Ecocrop code 17633

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION: A spiny deciduous or almost evergreen shrub or small
   tree reaching a height of 3-15 m, with a trunk diameter up to 40 cm or
   more. It has a spreading crown, drooping branches and reddish fruits.
   USES: It is mainly cultivated for its edible fruits. The fruit can be
   eaten fresh, dried like dates, or pickled. It can be made into flour
   meal, butter, cheeselike paste, and alcoholic as well as non-alcoholic
   beverage. The wood is use for constuction of rural houses, posts, tool
   handles, farm implements, saddletrees, sandals, turnery, and firewood
   and charcoal. The tree is planted as living fence, it is browsed by
   livestock and is mentioned as a possible agroforestry species. Bark
   contain tannin. Bark and leaves have medicinal properties. Leaves are
   fed to tasar silkworms and the tree hosts lac insects for shellac
   production. GROWING PERIOD: Perennial. Begins to bear after 6-8 years
   and increase yields to 15-20 years of age. COMMON NAMES: Indian jujube,
   Indian plum, Indian cherry, Chinese date, Chinese jujube, Dattero
   cinese, Datte chinoise, Azufaifa, Giuggiolo, Unabi, Jujube, Jujubier,
   Beri, Inu-natsume, Ber tree, Ber, De ber. FURTHER INF: Scientific
   synonyms: Z. mauratianus, Z. jujuba. Rhamnus jujuba. Indian jujube is
   indigenous to South Asia. It is normally found at elevations from sea
   level to 600 m, but can be found up to 1800 m. The tree is salt
   sensitive, but shoots of the plant can be grafted on the roots of Z.
   nummularia to allow fruit production on saline land. It is drought
   hardy and does not tolerate high air humidity. Fruit yields may range
   from 80-130 kg/tree per year.

   Sources

   FAO - Food and Agriculture Organization of the UN - Helping to build a
   world without hunger
